  see  Radwell   (1)."]},{"name":"Duddington","meanings":["English:  See  Doddington  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Doddington was born about 1380, in Stafford, Staffordshire, England, his father, Philip de Dodington, was 21 and his mother, Maud Matilda Laundey, was 31. He married Beatrix Batchelder before 1400. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. He died about 1428, in Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1380–about 1428":"umbes 1380–umbes 1428","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1400–1425":"1400–1425","1422–1461":"1422–1461","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1428–1476":"1428–1476","1430–1476":"1430–1476","–Female":"Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","before 1400":"enne 1400","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1425":"1425","about 1428":"umbes 1428","1422":"1422","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1430":"1430","1429":"